  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-section-2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 2 — Fetch Real Apple Stock Data\n",
    "\n",
    "We use `yfinance` to download 2 years of AAPL closing prices from Yahoo Finance — completely free, no API key needed.\n",
    "\n",
    "From that data we extract two numbers that drive the entire simulation:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Volatility (σ)** — how jumpy Apple's stock is day-to-day. Higher volatility = wider cone of possible outcomes.\n",
    "- **Drift (μ)** — Apple's average daily return, annualised. This is the underlying growth trend the simulation rides.\n",
    "\n",
    "Both are computed from **log returns** — the standard approach in quantitative finance because log returns are normally distributed and can be summed across time."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "code-fetch-data",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "print(f\"Downloading {CONFIG['lookback_years']} years of {CONFIG['ticker']} data...\")\n",
    "\n",
    "raw = yf.download(CONFIG['ticker'], period=f\"{CONFIG['lookback_years']}y\", progress=False)\n",
    "close = raw['Close'].squeeze()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Current price — starting point for simulation\n",
    "S0 = float(close.iloc[-1])\n",
    "\n",
    "# Log returns: log(price today / price yesterday)\n",
    "log_returns = np.log(close / close.shift(1)).dropna()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Annualise: multiply daily stats by sqrt(252) for vol, 252 for drift\n",
    "annual_vol   = float(log_returns.std()  * np.sqrt(252))\n",
    "annual_drift = float(log_returns.mean() * 252)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Store for use in later sections\n",
    "CONFIG['_S0']    = S0\n",
    "CONFIG['_vol']   = annual_vol\n",
    "CONFIG['_drift'] = annual_drift\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n  Current price      : ${S0:.2f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Annual volatility  : {annual_vol:.1%}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  Annual drift       : {annual_drift:.1%}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Quick plot of the price history\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 3))\n",
    "close.plot(ax=ax, color='#185fa5', linewidth=1.5)\n",
    "ax.set_title(f'AAPL Closing Price — Last {CONFIG[\"lookback_years\"]} Years', fontsize=12)\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Price (USD)')\n",
    "ax.set_facecolor('white')\n",
    "ax.grid(alpha=0.2)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "md-section-3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 3 — Historical Shock Calibration\n",
    "\n",
    "This is what makes this project different from a basic tutorial.\n",
    "\n",
    "Instead of making up a shock size, we measure what Apple's stock **actually did** during 5 real events that are comparable to a factory disruption:\n",
    "\n",
    "| Event | Why it's relevant |\n",
    "|-------|------------------|\n",
    "| COVID Crash (2020) | Largest ever supply chain freeze |\n",
    "| US-China Tariffs (2019) | Direct hit on China manufacturing costs |\n",
    "| iPhone Demand Warning (2019) | Apple itself signalled weaker production outlook |\n",
    "| China Factory Shutdown (2022) | Foxconn Zhengzhou lockdown, real production cut |\n",
    "| Tariff Shock (2025) | Most recent geopolitical manufacturing shock |\n",
    "\n",
    "We then take the **median drop** across supply chain events as our calibrated shock — a defensible, data-backed number."
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "code-historical-events",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "HISTORICAL_SHOCKS = {\n",
    "    'COVID Crash\\n(Feb–Mar 2020)': {\n",
    "        'start': '2020-02-19', 'end': '2020-03-23', 'category': 'supply_chain',\n",
    "        'description': 'Global pandemic declared. Factories and stores closed worldwide.'\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    'US-China Tariffs\\n(May 2019)': {\n",
    "        'start': '2019-05-06', 'end': '2019-06-03', 'category': 'geopolitical',\n",
    "        'description': 'Trump raised tariffs to 25% on Chinese goods. Apple heavily exposed.'\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    'iPhone Demand Warning\\n(Jan 2019)': {\n",
    "        'start': '2019-01-02', 'end': '2019-01-14', 'category': 'demand',\n",
    "        'description': 'Apple issued rare revenue warning citing weak China iPhone demand.'\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    'China Factory Shutdown\\n(Feb 2022)': {\n",
    "        'start': '2022-02-24', 'end': '2022-03-14', 'category': 'supply_chain',\n",
    "        'description': 'Zhengzhou Foxconn lockdowns disrupted iPhone 14 production.'\n",
    "    },\n",
    "    'Tariff Shock\\n(Apr 2025)': {\n",
    "        'start': '2025-04-03', 'end': '2025-04-09', 'category': 'geopolitical',\n",
    "        'description': 'Sweeping tariffs announced. Apple fell sharply on China exposure fears.'\n",
    "    },\n",
    "}\n",
    "\n",
    "print('Historical events defined.')"
   ]
  },

  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "code-measure-shocks",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "results = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for name, info in HISTORICAL_SHOCKS.items():\n",
    "    start = pd.to_datetime(info['start']) - timedelta(days=3)\n",
    "    end   = pd.to_datetime(info['end'])   + timedelta(days=3)\n",
    "    data  = yf.download('AAPL', start=start, end=end, progress=False)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if data.empty or len(data) < 2:\n",
    "        continue\n",
    "\n",
    "    c           = data['Close'].squeeze()\n",
    "    pct_change  = (float(c.iloc[-1]) - float(c.iloc[0])) / float(c.iloc[0]) * 100\n",
    "    results.append({\n",
    "        'event':      name,\n",
    "        'category':   info['category'],\n",
    "        'pct_change': round(pct_change, 2),\n",
    "        'start':      info['start'],\n",
    "        'end':        info['end'],\n",
    "    })\n",
    "    print(f\"  {name.replace(chr(10),' '):<40} {pct_change:+.1f}%\")\n",
    "\n",
    "shock_df = pd.DataFrame(results)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Calibrate: median of supply_chain events\n",
    "supply_chain = shock_df[shock_df['category'] == 'supply_chain']\n",
    "calibrated_shock = supply_chain['pct_change'].median() / 100\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"\\n  Calibrated shock (median of supply_chain events): {calibrated_shock:+.2%}\")\n",
    "CONFIG['_calibrated_shock'] = calibrated_shock"
   ]
  },

