    "---\n",
    "## Section 7 — Results & Interpretation\n",
    "\n",
    "### How to read the output\n",
    "\n",
    "**The cone of paths** shows the range of possible futures. The wider the cone, the more uncertain the outcome. Most of the width comes from Apple's natural volatility (~28% annually) — not from the factory shock itself.\n",
    "\n",
    "**The key insight this project demonstrates:**\n",
    "\n",
    "> A factory representing ~8% of Apple's total production capacity, when partially offset by other facilities and read as a China risk reduction, produces a near-negligible shock. Apple's underlying growth momentum dominates the 1-year outlook.\n",
    "\n",
    "**What would change the result significantly:**\n",
    "- `factory_share` above 0.25 — a truly large facility\n",
    "- `replacement_cap` near 0 — no other factories can absorb the loss\n",
    "- A strongly negative sentiment composite (e.g. -0.5) — markets are already panicking\n",
    "\n",
    "### Limitations to mention if presenting this project\n",
    "\n",
    "1. **GBM assumes log-normal returns** — real crashes are more extreme than the model predicts\n",
    "2. **TextBlob is general-purpose NLP** — a finance-specific model (FinBERT) would be more accurate\n",
    "3. **Historical shocks are measured over different windows** — not normalised to a fixed time period\n",
    "4. **The china_exit_bonus is subjective** — based on analyst commentary, not a hard data point\n",]
  }
